Names><gtr:surname>Lewis</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG010331%2F1"><gtr:id>9C2F7461-EE7A-4193-A973-469E7C0017A9</gtr:id><gtr:title>Understanding income distribution in modern capitalist economies</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G010331/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This project develops Lewis's PhD thesis, ESRC award PTA-030-2003-00598, which is a theoretical and comparative empirical study into the distribution of income in modern capitalist economies. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Theoretically this research rejects neoclassical economics and classical labour theories of value as explanations of the returns to different categories of workers and capital. It develops an alternative framework where industries generate different degrees of surplus within economies, which are shared between types of workers and capital dependent upon national institutions, particularly the systems of corporate governance, industrial relations, education and training and inter-company competition.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>A detailed industry level comparison of employment, wages and return on capital over the last thirty years will be undertaken, expanding the existing research from the UK, US, France and Germany to the twenty-five EU member states, US and Japan. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research has significance for social scientists interested in understanding the causes of distribution and inequality within and between national economies, and the potential for different 'varieties of capitalism' to alter market outcomes. It will be used to engage in UK policy debates; highlighting the limitations of child poverty reduction through welfare to work reforms, the limited viability of asset based welfare, and informing emerging debates on industrial policy.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-07-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>74722</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>1CFECC81-6C77-41A5-B2D0-A52E7AFA715D</gtr:id><gtr:title>Neoliberalism in Crisis</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/d3dddbe4c57e30c945f3277e6c8e3113"><gtr:id>d3dddbe4c57e30c945f3277e6c8e3113</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Lewis P</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>545ceba72e4342.37680646</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>816A2ED3-D603-45D8-AAF6-7675C36A8D5A</gtr:id><gtr:title>'Global Security' in Encyclopedia of Life Support Systems (EOLSS)</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/8aa9a18ee76884afb1df05b7540941dc"